@1g 2.2 trees
@1h trees: connected graph containing no cycles
@1i forest: graph containing no cycles
@1j a connected forest is a tree
@1k rooted trees
@1l one vertex is root
@1m spanning tree
@1n tree that includes all vertices of a connected graph
@1o 2.2.2 props of trees [pg 119]
@1p a graph $T$ is a tree if and only if between every
pair of distinct verts of $T$ there is a distinct path [prop 2.2.2]
@1q assume $T$ is a tree
@1r $u$ and $v$ distinct vertices
@1s show there is a unique path between $u$ and $v$
@1t there is a path
@1u not more than one path
@1v suppose there are 2 paths, get contradiction
@1w there is some first vertex $u'$ after which 2 paths diverge
@1x since both paths end at $v$, there is some vertex after $u'$
that they have in common, called $v'$
@1y the 2 paths from $u'$ to $v'$ form a cycle, contradicting
assumption that $T$ is a tree
@1z converse: if between every pair of distincrt verts of $T$
there is a unique path, then $T$ is a tree
@20 if and only if means 2 implications must be proven
@21 assume hypothesis: between every pair of distinct verts of T,
there is a unique path
@22 prove $T$ is a tree, by showing it is connected and contains
no cycles
@23 $T$ is connected because there is a path between every
pair of verts
@24 assume $T$ has cycles for contradiction
@25 $u$ and $v$ distinct verts in a cycle of $T$
@26 can get from $u$ to $v$ clockwise or counter-clockwise around the cycle
@27 2 paths from $u$ to $v$, contradicting assumption
@28 existence of paths
@29 uniqueness of paths
@2a just consider graphs no cycles (forest)
@2b use parts of proof that explore uniqueness of paths, not existence
@2c corallary 2.2.3: graph f is a forest
if and only if between every pair of verts there is at most one path
